      "pass": 1,
      "prose": "I'll work through this case using the croup guideline.The note matches the moderate severity row cleanly (inspiratory stridor at rest, mild suprasternal/intercostal recession, alert and mildly distressed). Differential check is clean: clear URTI prodrome, no drooling/tripod/toxic appearance (against epiglottitis), no high fever or toxic features (against bacterial tracheitis), no choking history and symmetric chest (against foreign body), no allergen exposure or urticaria (against anaphylaxis).Assessment: 3-year-old with classic moderate viral croup — typical URTI prodrome, barky cough, hoarseness, inspiratory stridor at rest, mild recession, well-perfused and alert with SpO₂ 97%. No features pointing to epiglottitis, bacterial tracheitis, foreign body, or anaphylaxis on the must-not-miss differential. Severity is **moderate**.\n\nPlan: Single oral dose of dexamethasone per the Starship moderate-croup rule. Keep him calm on the parent's lap (avoid distressing examination), supportive care for the URTI, and observe in a monitored area through the post-steroid window. No nebulised adrenaline indicated at current severity.\n\nReassessment: At the scheduled review, focus on whether stridor at rest and recession are settling versus persisting or worsening, the trajectory of work of breathing and oxygenation, and mental state (agitation or unusual quietness are both concerning). Escalate immediately if any signs of severe disease emerge — do not wait for the scheduled review. Note the universal rail that moderate croup is not discharged overnight, so the disposition decision will need to account for time of day.",
